Actually, there's a simpler approach: save any existing EXIT trap, then set a new one that calls both the saved trap and RunCompleted. This is a standard bash pattern:

```bash
_evolve_exit_trap() {
    local exit_code=$?
    record_state_event "RunCompleted" ...
    # call any previously-set trap
    [ -n "$_PREV_EXIT_TRAP" ] && eval "$_PREV_EXIT_TRAP"
    return $exit_code
}
_PREV_EXIT_TRAP="$(trap -p EXIT | sed "s/trap -- '\(.*\)' EXIT/\1/")"
trap '_evolve_exit_trap' EXIT
```

